column6: thank you. your voices brought me out of denial.

column1: 28089;instagram;2019-02-27 23:45:53;FALSE;"#oprahwinfrey will sit down with the two men at the center of an already controversial michael jackson documentary set to debut on hbo next week. ""oprah winfrey presents: after neverland"" will be a conversation with wade robson and james safechuck
column2: the subjects of the two-part documentary ""leaving neverland."" the film examines disturbing claims by safechuck and robson that jackson sexually abused them over a period of several years when they were children.
along with the project's director dan reed
column3: will appear ""before an audience of survivors of sexual abuse and others whose lives have been impacted by it
column4: according to hbo and winfrey's own network
column5: who are partnering on the special. (cnn and hbo share parent company warnermedia.) ""leaving neverland"" first screened at the sundance film festival and revived conversation about whether jackson was a predatory pedophile.

column1: jackson's family has denied the allegations and condemned the documentary
column4: in reference to sworn statements made by both safechuck and robson while jackson was alive that he did not molest them.

column1: robson made statements in support of jackson to investigators first in the '90s and testified in support of jackson at his 2005 trial
column2: where he was acquitted of child molestation and related charges. safechuck at one point also denied he was molested by jackson to investigators.

column1: the two filed separate civil lawsuits against jackson's estate that were dismissed on technical grounds and remain under appeal.
the jackson estate has filed a suit against hbo over the documentary.

column3: director tyler perry and 200 men came together as survivors of childhood sexual abuse on her daytime talk show.

column1: she also famously interviewed jackson in 1993 at his neverland ranch.
the special debuts simultaneously on hbo and own at 10 p.m. est on march 4

column1: 28093;instagram;2019-02-27 23:48:18;FALSE;"letâ€™s talk about the power of oneâ˜ï¸ you always hear those stories in history where someone did or said something profound and it ended great suffering and injustice for others. that one person was all it took to change history forever. it may take one person to start something
column2: but it takes more than one to end it. everyone has a cause that they care deeply about. something we support because we believe it will make the world a better place.

column3: that is what we tell ourselves as we work our way into institutional stress
column5: and burnout. we canâ€™t stop because if we do

column1: 28116;instagram;2019-02-28 00:14:14;FALSE;"can we talk depression for a minute?â£
i have to get this out.â£
i have so many women come to me and tell me they are â€œdepressed.â€ they have seen doctors (sometimes multiple)
column3: who have all agreed with the diagnosis and have suggested medication. while i truly believe that medication can be life saving in certain circumstances
column4: there is something very disturbing about all of this in regards to the women i have been speaking with. you see
column5: every single one of these women have experienced a huge life altering eventâ€¦divorce

column2: this is not depression. you are fucking sad. it is human to feel deep
column3: heart wrenching sadness at times. especially times when we are grievingâ€¦â£

column1: grieving a marriage which also comes with grieving the picture you painted for the future of yourself and your familyâ£
grieving the loss of our own power and the safety of our body from being sexually assaultedâ£
grieving through the thoughts that our bodies are broken because we canâ€™t â€œdo what women are supposed to doâ€ by carrying a childâ£
grieving the death of someone you loved so deeply and sometimes because of that
column2: questioning and grieving your spiritual knowing and belief systemâ£

column1: grieving the financial security and lifestyle you once had due to an unexpected change in positionâ£

column3: and accepting that the people you thought would always be there

column1: it is sadness that catapults us into brokenness
column2: and not brokenness as in needing to be fixed
column3: but brokenness as in being completely broken open. open to not only being able to acknowledge and grow from your own pain
column4: but also being able to acknowledge the pain of others as well. and in those moments
column5: you truly understand the depth of happiness
column6: the longing for intimate personal connections and gratitude for life itself.â£

column2: nuns talk about abuse by priests

column1: by nicole winfield and rodney muhumuza
vatican city (ap) â€” the nun no longer goes to confession regularly
column2: after an italian priest forced himself on her while she was at her most vulnerable: recounting her sins to him in a university classroom nearly 20 years ago.
the sister only told her provincial superior and her spiritual director
column3: silenced by the catholic churchâ€™s culture of secrecy
column4: her vows of obedience and her own fear
column5: repulsion and shame. â€œit opened a great wound inside of me
column6: â€ she told the associated press. â€œi pretended it didnâ€™t happen.â€ after decades of silence
column7: the nun is one of a handful worldwide to come forward recently on an issue that the catholic church has yet to come to terms with: the sexual abuse of religious sisters by priests and bishops. an ap examination has found that cases have emerged in europe
column10: demonstrating that the problem is global and pervasive
column11: thanks to the universal tradition of sistersâ€™ second-class status in the catholic church and their ingrained subservience to the men who run it.

column1: some nuns are now finding their voices
column2: buoyed by the #metoo movement and the growing recognition that adults can be victims of sexual abuse when there is an imbalance of power in a relationship. the sisters are going public in part because of years of inaction by church leaders
column3: even after major studies on the problem in africa were reported to the vatican in the 1990s.

column1: the issue has flared in the wake of scandals over the sexual abuse of children
column3: including revelations that one of the most prominent american cardinals
column5: sexually abused and harassed his seminarians.

column1: the extent of the abuse of nuns is unclear

column1: 28391;instagram;2019-02-28 07:29:37;FALSE;"wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014
column2: when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

column1: documents show the john bolton super pac
column2: which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton
column4: 700 in 2014 for ""behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging."" those services included strategies that broke individual voters into ""clusters"" based on what messages would resonate with them.

column1: 28503;instagram;2019-02-18 22:25:41;FALSE;"the #metoo movement that has caught fire in the last couple of years is a statement of this kind of love. a love comprised of clearly stating this is where i end and you begin and you don't get to cross this line without my permission. a love comprised of compassion for ourselves and the traumas we have experienced at the hands of (mostly) men. a love comprised of empathy for others with similar experiences and especially for those who are able to speak up and out.
it is a love that seeks more than justice. it is a love that seeks our humanity. /../

column1: 28652;instagram;2019-02-18 20:18:57;FALSE;"have you watched this red table conversation yet?  this is the kind of conversation we think needs to be happening in workplaces.  we need to really listen to and validate the experiences of *all* people who identify as women
column2: especially in the workplace.  as @rachel.cargle shares in the video: none of us is free until all of us are free.â €

we see people who are completely unaware of their own privilege and thus don't believe it exists. being unaware of privilege is exactly the point: it is exceedingly common for people who benefit from privilege to be completely and blissfully unaware of it or how privilege shows up on a daily basis. it is also not up to women of color to teach
column4: or justify their experiences or the fact that privilege exists.  further
column5: it is not up to women of color to write the guidebook or draw out a path for white people (particularly white women) to confront their own privilege and begin to act in allyship. do the work. â €

column1: watch the video and tell us what affected you the most. we want to have more conversations like this red table talk within hruprise.  we have to be willing to get uncomfortable and have real dialogue.  what do you want to discuss?  we hear from many of you that you take these posts in to spark discussion with your hr teams.  what courageous conversations do you need to have?â €
(story: three women from diverse backgrounds join the red table to discuss the concept of white privilege
column2: and how it affects the relationships between white women and women of color. https://buff.ly/2xa41vl)â €

column2: i'd never be that girl. that i was strong and tough enough to fight back. then i became her. it all started with one punch to the arm. and him saying he was half asleep and would never hurt me. i believed it
column3: even tho i knew of the girls before. but i thought this is not how abusive relationships start out. if it was going be bad it be like that from the start. at the time i thought i was worth being a different man for. worth changing bad habits. reality
column5: that's up to them. the one punch lead to black eyes
column6: and bloody noses. hits so hard my glasses would break. random items coming at my face from hammers to kids toys. lying for him became my bad habit. covering up bruises became my past time
column7: cause i knew if anyone saw i would have to face the fact i couldn't change him. till one day i saw the light. i refuse to be this girl anymore. i'm worth changing for

column1: 28774;instagram;2019-02-18 19:16:09;FALSE;"should you take your ex back?? not unless they can point to the visable and constant change they've made in their life.

column2: just to do it again a few days later. i believe she wanted to change
column3: but because she kept hanging with friends who did the same
column5: and never addressed her broken upbringing...the change was never going to be real or constant.

column3: a nonprofit whose mission was to educate girls and women. she also opened a home for widows and a rehabilitation center for women.

column2: i was obsessed with music. i remember awakening to the world of pop music in the 5th grade because of the eurythmics. in the 6th grade
column3: i saved up my money and bought a cheap boom box and recorded songs off the radio (that was an activity all in itself). in high school
column4: i spent most of my money on music
column5: and i would even forego food to use my lunch money for cassette tapes (just to get one song). music is what carried me through the hardest times
column6: listening to the pain and joy of the artists translated into something i could feel.

column1: i was often the driver for my friends in our old brown vw vanagon (often found on the side of the road on family trips
column2: teaching me valuable lessons about the kindness of strangers). we called it ""the party bus."" in it
column3: we would blast my mix tapes and sing along.

column1: i loved making mix tapes for my friends. and there were certain albums and certain songs that defined certain times for me. after the most difficult challenges of my teen years (including being raped by someone i had shared the darkest parts of my soul with)
column3: which still embody how i feel about love. yep. i am still an idealist

column2: i struggled with some more complicated feelings
column4: music was there to hold me. you can listen to the playlist i made starting in september 2017 by clicking on the link in my profile.

28863;instagram;2019-02-18 17:59:00;FALSE;my assault occured over a decade ago. i sought treatment following the assault but it wasn't enough
column2: though i didn't know that at the time. it changed who i was at the very core of myself and i believed myself broken for years. i believed what happened was my fault and that made me unworthy of love and belonging. i worked hard to try to make myself into someone who would be worthy of being loved but always found myself lacking.

column1: being raped by a trusted friend tends to change a person. i was young and we live in a society that glorifies rape culture. even though i worked with trauma victims at the time
column4: that i deserved what happened to me. that 22 year old girl still exists inside me
column5: in pain. i'm trying to help her heal by allowing her (and myself) the compassion i'd allow anyone else.

column2: i was diagnosed with ptsd. i've been in therapy every week since then
column3: following a treatment protocol initially developed for combat veterans. it's been extremely helpful. i'm finally starting to unravel the years of toxic thought patterns. i'm finally starting to believe that i am enough. i'm finally starting to believe that i never deserved what happened to me. i know i still have a long way to go but i'm finally starting to heal those deep-seated wounds.

column2: it's never too late to seek treatment for trauma. it's never too late to heal. sharing my story is part of my healing.

column1: 28903;instagram;2019-02-18 17:26:55;FALSE;"former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel
column2: but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

column1: in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23
column2: flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia
column3: and kushner spoke with kim darroch
column4: the british ambassador to the united states
column5: according to diplomats familiar with the conversations
column6: who spoke on condition of anonymity.

column1: the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump
column2: who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric
column3: took office on jan. 20. it failed
column4: with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

column1: the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move
column2: egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution
column3: prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

column1: a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a ""high level"" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.
according to court documents made public on friday
column2: a member of trump's presidential transition team
column3: later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner
column4: told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments
column6: to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

column1: 28952;instagram;2019-02-18 16:29:17;FALSE;"former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel
column2: but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

column1: in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23
column2: flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia
column3: and kushner spoke with kim darroch
column4: the british ambassador to the united states
column5: according to diplomats familiar with the conversations
column6: who spoke on condition of anonymity.

column1: the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump
column2: who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric
column3: took office on jan. 20. it failed
column4: with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

column1: the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move
column2: egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution
column3: prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

column1: a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a ""high level"" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.
according to court documents made public on friday
column2: a member of trump's presidential transition team
column3: later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner
column4: told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments
column6: to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

column1: flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day
